<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Edited to fix broken posticon  -Z</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A> at: 3/26/02 4:16:48 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 163<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/8/02 9:19:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=18.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Electricity from Space.</span><hr size=1> What did you have in mind?  Solar Powered Satellite system in orbit<br>
that microwave beams the power to receiving stations on Earth?  Would<br>
be prohibitively expensive to build with current launch costs... if<br>
nuclear powered rockets could lower the launch costs drastically then<br>
it might be feasible... would depend on how such a strong microwave<br>
beam would interact with the atmosphere and environment...<br>
<br>
&quot;EcoWackie Newsflash... an endangered species of bird is now believed<br>
extinct after the last remaining flock flew through the microwave beam<br>
transmitted from the Tesla SPS station in Earth orbit today... I guess<br>
you could say their goose was cooked.&quot; <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubestonnet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bestonnet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 143<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/8/02 10:19:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=18.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Electricity from Space.</span><hr size=1> The beam wouldn't be strong enough to kill any birds that fly through it.<br>
<br>
Some small birds might actually stay in the beam during winter because it would warm them up a little, just like the people who stand in front of radar dishes to keep warm. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fusion Starship Captain</span><br>  Posts: 347<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/10/02 5:47:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=18.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Electricity from Space.</span><hr size=1> True. The microwave will probably be spread out as much as a kilometre or more on reaching the surface of Earth. It's a wasteful process. Solar power cells convert photons to electricity, electricity gets converted to microwaves, microwaves get converted at reciever back to electricity then finally to whatever kinetic or heat energy it is required for in the home.<br>
<br>
On the plus side it is free power. Once you pay off the cells. Ideally, we would build them from space resources in the first place. Just take the industrial infrastructure and difficult to manufacture items with us by rocket. <br>
<br>
Could the massive arrays be placed in a solar orbit which avoids debris? Micrmeteoroid impacts could devastate such a programme. Otherwise the panels might be expected to last many decades. There's no reason why all Earth's power couldn't be supplied in this fashion. No ugly windmills or solar panels taking away the beauty of our natural environment. No need to clutter rooftops and every other square inch of space we can locate. We just build massive arrays in space measuring many kilometres in length.<br>
<br>
Ofcourse, it might be prudent having nuclear power plants as 'backup generators' should something disastrous happen. Say, an Asteroid swarm turns the power grid off at the source. <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
<br>Nuclear power is the next logical step for serious space travel. The technology required to colonise the solar system exists now!

<br><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace">NUCLEARSPACE</a>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubestonnet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bestonnet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 170<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/11/02 1:12:05 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=18.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Electricity from Space.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> True. The microwave will probably be spread out as much as a kilometre or more on reaching the surface of Earth.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Probably a lot larger.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> It's a wasteful process. Solar power cells convert photons to electricity, electricity gets converted to microwaves, microwaves get converted at reciever back to electricity then finally to whatever kinetic or heat energy it is required for in the home.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
63% DC-DC efficency is pretty good although the total efficency when you factor in the PV panels is much lower then that.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Could the massive arrays be placed in a solar orbit which avoids debris?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
There really aren't that many things that would hit it in space.  It'll probably lose less then 1% of it's power per decade by hits and even then it's a trival job to repair the damage.  Just replace the broken cell.  Also cover the panels in glass so they don't get destroyed by radiation.<br>
<br>
Only problem is that SPS would be useless if our anti-nuclear group somehow succeeds <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fusion Starship Captain</span><br>  Posts: 396<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/12/02 8:53:05 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=18.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.website-wisdom.com/graphics/icons/simpsons/town/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Electricity from Space.</span><hr size=1> What about other sources of electricity 'not of this Earth'?<br>
<br>
Hydrocarbons are abundant. So are other volatiles. Would it be worthwhile making electricity with large generators for similar transmission to Earth? Could we tap into any other source of energy and turn it to electricity. What about the massive volcanic activity of Io or the storms of Jupiter. The universe is a pretty violent place and violence requires energy.  <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
